  <article class="digital-human-rights">
    <h2 class="loud-text heading-2xl">We Uphold Digital Human Rights</h2> 
    <div class="body-l" style="color: var(--colors-ink-30);">The internet grew up. Now it’s time for it to grow a conscience: Digital Rights are Human Rights encoded in systems. They aren't nice-to-haves. <b style="color: var(--colors-indigo-40);">Without them, an operation can neither scale nor last — let alone be trusted.</b></div>
    <dl class="digital-human-rights-list">
      <dt class="digital-human-rights-list-item">Open: I can speak freely</dt>
      <dd class="digital-human-rights-list-definition">I can share my thoughts, ideas, and work without needing permission — and without fear of censorship or erasure.</dd>
      <dt class="digital-human-rights-list-item">Secure: I can speak privately</dt>
      <dd class="digital-human-rights-list-definition">I can share, organize, and express myself without being tracked, recorded, or overheard.</dd>
      <dt class="digital-human-rights-list-item">Personal: I own my data</dt>
      <dd class="digital-human-rights-list-definition">My files, messages, and memories belong to me. I decide who can see them — and I can take that access away at any time.</dd>
      <dt class="digital-human-rights-list-item">Independent: I connect directly</dt>
      <dd class="digital-human-rights-list-definition">I use systems that link people and devices without needing companies, platforms, or governments in the middle.</dd>
      <dt class="digital-human-rights-list-item">Trustworthy: I can verify what happens</dt>
      <dd class="digital-human-rights-list-definition">I don’t have to guess or assume. Every action leaves a trail I can check for myself.</dd>
      <dt class="digital-human-rights-list-item">Selective: I decide what to share</dt>
      <dd class="digital-human-rights-list-definition">My information is private by default. Others only see what I choose to show — and only as much as they need.</dd>
      <dt class="digital-human-rights-list-item">Resilient: I can count on my tools</dt>
      <dd class="digital-human-rights-list-definition">My systems keep working — even offline, under pressure, or outside the mainstream. They don’t break when someone says so.</dd>
      <dt class="digital-human-rights-list-item">Portable: I own my identity</dt>
      <dd class="digital-human-rights-list-definition">My identity moves with me. It’s under my control, not tied to any platform — and I decide who can use it.</dd>
      <dt class="digital-human-rights-list-item">Safe: I can define my boundaries</dt>
      <dd class="digital-human-rights-list-definition">I choose how others can reach me, interact with me, and affect my experience. My tools help me set limits, avoid harm, and stay in control.</dd>
    </dl>
  </article>
